    },
    {
      "step_id": "be68c202",
      "step_index": 2,
      "step_type": "reasoning",
      "content": "## 2) SAR reasoning (why features affect CYP2D6 inhibition)\nCYP2D6 inhibitors commonly have:\n- a **strongly protonatable basic N** (often tertiary amine; pKa ~8\u201310) to form ionic interaction with the acidic residue in the CYP2D6 active site (notably Asp301),\n- plus **one or more lipophilic/aromatic rings** for hydrophobic/\u03c0 interactions,\n- sometimes an HBD near the basic center.",
      "tool_name": null,
      "tool_input": null,
      "tool_output": null,
      "timestamp": "2026-02-26T19:47:12.513778+00:00"
    },
    {
      "step_id": "f5de45e5",
      "step_index": 3,
      "step_type": "reasoning",
      "content": "This molecule **does have**:\n- **Aromatic/lipophilic surface** (two rings, two chloros, a methoxy) \u2192 supports binding in hydrophobic pockets.",
      "tool_name": null,
      "tool_input": null,
      "tool_output": null,
      "timestamp": "2026-02-26T19:47:12.513791+00:00"
    },
    {
      "step_id": "db74b87d",
      "step_index": 4,
      "step_type": "reasoning",
      "content": "But it **does not have**:\n- a **strongly protonatable amine**. The only basic site is a **pyridine N**, which is typically **not protonated much at physiological pH**, weakening the key ionic anchoring interaction associated with many potent CYP2D6 inhibitors.",
      "tool_name": null,
      "tool_input": null,
      "tool_output": null,
      "timestamp": "2026-02-26T19:47:12.513804+00:00"
    },
    {
      "step_id": "d31f3452",
      "step_index": 5,
      "step_type": "reasoning",
      "content": "Also, the **amide** can reduce basicity/overall cationic character and can impose a relatively planar, polar linker that may favor other CYPs but is less characteristic of strong CYP2D6 inhibition.",
      "tool_name": null,
      "tool_input": null,
      "tool_output": null,
      "timestamp": "2026-02-26T19:47:12.513816+00:00"
    },
    {
